<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-05-13T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-05-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="7" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d7">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">
                            <persName corresp="#p_LFAWD1">Leahy</persName> Papers: Telegram</note>
                        <head>No. 7 <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_CMWS1" type="from">Churchill</persName> to President <persName corresp="#p_THS1" type="to">Truman</persName>
                            </hi><note n="1" xml:id="d7fn1">Sent by the United States Military
                                Attaché, London, via Army channels.</note>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                            </seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-05-13">13th May
                                1945</date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Prime Minister to President <persName corresp="#p_THS1">Truman</persName>. Personal and top secret. Number 46. Your number
                                36.<note n="2" xml:id="d7fn2">
                                <ref target="#d5">Document No. 5</ref>.</note>
                            <list>
                                <label>1.</label>
                                <item>F. D. R.<note n="3" xml:id="d7fn3">i. e., <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName>.</note> promised
                                    me he would visit England before he went to France or, as it has
                                    now become, Germany. We should feel disappointed if you did not
                                    come to us. But having regard to the gravity of the next few
                                    months, no question of ceremonial should intervene with the
                                    organized sequence of events. Therefore I am for the conference
                                    of the three as soon as possible and wherever possible.</item>
                                <label>2.</label>
                                <item>In this case I consider that we should try to bring the
                                    meeting off some time in June, and I hope your fiscal year will
                                    not delay it. We greatly hope you will come to England
                                    later.</item>
                                <label>3.</label>
                                <item>I agree that our Ambassadors should do their utmost to induce
                                        <persName corresp="#p_SMIV2">Stalin</persName> to propose
                                    the meeting, and instructions will be given accordingly by us. I
                                    doubt very much whether he will accede. Time is on his side if
                                    he digs in while we melt away.</item>
                                <label>4.</label>
                                <item>I look forward to your meeting with <persName corresp="#p_EA1">Eden</persName>[.]</item>
                            </list>
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>